<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I read tire size numbers?", answer: "A tire size like 225/45R17 means: 225 is the tire width in millimeters, 45 is the aspect ratio (sidewall height is 45% of the width), R means radial construction, and 17 is the rim diameter in inches. So a 225/45R17 tire has a 225mm width, a sidewall height of 101.25mm (225 x 0.45), and fits a 17-inch wheel." },
  { question: "How does tire size affect speedometer accuracy?", answer: "If you switch to larger tires, your vehicle actually travels farther per wheel revolution than the speedometer expects, making it read slower than your actual speed. Conversely, smaller tires make the speedometer read faster than actual speed. A 3% diameter increase means your actual speed is about 3% higher than displayed. Most manufacturers allow up to 3% speedometer error." },
  { question: "Can I put different size tires on my car?", answer: "You can change tire sizes within certain limits. Generally, the overall diameter should stay within 3% of the original tire to avoid speedometer errors, clearance issues, and drivetrain stress. Many enthusiasts use the plus-sizing method: increasing rim diameter while decreasing sidewall height to maintain the same overall diameter." },
  { question: "What happens if I use bigger tires?", answer: "Larger tires increase ground clearance and can improve off-road capability, but they also affect speedometer accuracy (reads slower), may rub on fenders or suspension components, can reduce acceleration due to increased rotational mass, and may trigger ABS or traction control issues. Fuel economy typically decreases slightly with larger tires." },
  { question: "What is tire revolutions per mile?", answer: "Revolutions per mile is how many times a tire completes a full rotation to travel one mile. It is calculated by dividing 63,360 (inches per mile) by the tire circumference in inches. Smaller tires have more revolutions per mile. This number matters because the vehicle's computer uses wheel rotations to calculate speed and distance, so changing tire size affects these readings." }
]) %>

